The '''Kentucky Athletic Hall of Fame''' is a sports [[hall of fame]] for the U.S. state of [[Kentucky]] established in 1963.<ref> {{cite news|title=Hall of Fame Inducts Reese And Cartmell |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/109037219/|newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]]|date=December 18, 1963|page=24|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 12, 2017 }} {{Subscription required}}</ref> The hall "recognizes athletes and sports figures who were born in, or who played their respective sport, in the state of Kentucky."<ref>{{cite web|title=Kentucky Athletic Hall of Fame|url=https://kahof.com/|publisher=Kentucky Athletic Hall of Fame|accessdate=June 28, 2018}}</ref> Individuals are inducted annually at a banquet in [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]] and receive a bronze plaque inside Louisville's [[Freedom Hall]].<ref name=2016class>{{cite news|title=Kentucky Athletic Hall of Fame inducts 2016 class Thursday|url=http://www.kentucky.com/sports/other-sports/article81239987.html|accessdate=January 17, 2017|work=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=June 1, 2016}}</ref>
Honorees have included Louisville native [[Muhammad Ali]];<ref>{{cite news|last1=Boeck|first1=Greg|title=What I learned about Muhammad Ali over 50 years|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/boxing/2016/06/08/muhammad-ali-louisville-phoenix/85603632/|accessdate=January 17, 2017|work=USA Today|date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> [[American football]] player and coach [[Bo McMillin]] (who played for [[Centre College]] in [[Danville, Kentucky]]);<ref>{{cite news|title=Bo McMillin '22 inducted into the Kentucky Athletic Hall of Fame|url=https://www.centre.edu/bo-mcmillin-22-inducted-into-the-kentucky-athletic-hall-of-fame/|accessdate=January 17, 2017|publisher=Centre College|date=June 20, 2013}}</ref> and basketball player and coach [[Pat Riley]], who played in college for the [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball]] team.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cox|first1=Earl|title=Pat Riley able to attend Kron wake|url=http://www.themountaineagle.com/news/2007-12-12/sports/043.html|accessdate=January 18, 2017|work=The Mountain Eagle|date=December 12, 2007}}</ref>
Inducted in the 2015 class were tennis player [[Mel Purcell]], women's basketball coach Paul Sanderford, basketball player Sharon Garland, college basketball manager Lloyd Gardner, [[Major League Baseball]] umpire [[Randy Marsh]], track and field athlete Shandelier Boyd Smith, and [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]]'s [[Keeneland Race Course]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Osborne|first1=Glenn|title=Sports Notes: Kentucky Athletics Hall of Fame Class of 2015 features WKU's red tint|url=http://www.nkytribune.com/2015/05/sports-notes-kentucky-athletics-hall-of-fame-class-of-2015-features-wkus-red-tint/|accessdate=January 18, 2017|work=Northern Kentucky Tribune|date=May 12, 2015}}</ref>
The 2016 class included American football player [[Shaun Alexander]], basketball player [[Darel Carrier]], college basketball coach Scott Davenport, basketball player Kyra Elzy, high school basketball coach Philip Haywood, [[Kentucky Wesleyan Panthers men's basketball|Kentucky Wesleyan basketball]] play-by-play announcer Joel Utley, and the Lakeside Swim Club.<ref name=2016class/>
