{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = St Ann's Ground | nickname = | country = England | image = | location = [[Barnes, London|Barnes]], [[Surrey]] | establishment = 1889 (first recorded match) | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year1 = 1890 | club1 = [[Lyric Club]] | date = 28 August | year = 2010 | source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/292_f.html Ground profile }}
'''St Ann's Ground''' was a [[cricket]] ground at [[Barnes, London|Barnes]], Surrey (now in the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]). In 1889 the Lyric Club played the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] in a non first-class match.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/292_misc.html Other matches played on St Ann's Ground]</ref> The only [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match held at the ground came in 1890 when the Lyric Club played the touring [[Australia national cricket team|Australians]],<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/292_f.html First-Class Matches played on St Ann's Ground]</ref> which the Lyric Club won by 96 runs.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/3/3614.html Lyric Club v Australians, 1890]</ref> The final important match at the ground, in 1892, was between the Lyric Club and the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]]. The ground was located within the grounds of St Ann's House, which in the early 1900s it was built over. The approximate location of the house today would be near Lyric Road and St Ann's Road, which are near the [[River Thames]].
